Open1:
I am an ardent Trump-hater. I gave him the benefit of the doubt in 2016, but before 2017, I was thinking that he would be kicked out of office. I was shocked to find out how many of my friends and relatives voted for him, even in 2020!  So, I read about politics, but I don't discuss politics with anyone unless I know they also disapprove of him - - and his cronies. 

I don't mind some entertainment news, but mostly it's garbage. I really, really don't need to know anything about any of the Kardashians. The entertainment news I really love, for example, is reading about how Lin Manuel-Miranda decided to write the play, Hamilton. If the entertainment news has something to do with history, I'm in! I liked reading about the differences in the two versions of West Side Story - one from the 60's and the current one. But it's more about the culture than the private lives of the actors. 

I love to travel and am very interested in other places and cultures. But I rarely share any of the information. One, because so many people think the US is by far the best country to live in, and I disagree. They are usually very close-minded about other countries or cultures. Two, because some of my friends and relatives would love to be able to travel, but can't afford it.

I like to read and hear news about business, but sometimes it is just over my head. I realize that there are so many variables when it comes to, inflation for example. I know that it is not one thing that can "fix" inflation. It can't be blamed on one president or one party. I do wonder about so many companies reporting record profits (like some of the oil companies) while at the same time raising prices. It doesn't make sense. But I try to read and understand business and finance as much as possible. I do like it when I discover something that really helps me. For example, in the fall I read that I-bonds were paying over 9% interest. I was sure to tell lots of people about it and I opened a Treasury Direct account to deposit what I could. 

I do like to read about science and the environment, but at times it just gets too depressing. So many of my friends and relatives think that climate change is a hoax. I just think it is something that we CAN'T GET WRONG. It's not a Democrat thing or a Republican thing. It's something that we really need to pay attention to before it's too late.
Studying1: I think you were trying to see how we perceived the changes in the numbers in the graphs and how we would project those changes into the future. I did find it difficult to separate what I THINK I know from what the graphs showed.
Studying2: I'm not sure. Maybe you wanted to know if we shared things that we believed in whether they were factual or not?  I don't know.
Open2:
It seems that people are more and more likely to believe something that they read on social media than what comes from actual studies?  I am surprised at what some of my friends and relatives say about politics or science or just about anything. It's always, "Well, on Facebook...."  
I joined the Johnson & Johnson Covid vaccine study in November 2020. So many people that I was "crazy" because it was "So experimental". I just don't get it.

Open1:
On the graphs, I was trying to determine if any patterns were visible in 2 or 5 year periods. I chose these numbers because they divide conveniently into 10 and 20. This made my value assumptions much easier to generalize. I felt the 2 year periods was too close to 1 and was not helpful in reducing the work effort. But they could be used in groups of 2 to 4 which would give 4 to 8 year ranges. I felt this gave me a bit more flexibility in looking into identifying pattern grouping. 

I did feel successful in about half of the graphs. On the other half,  I felt the pattern was quite self evident as to the direction the graph was headed into and this made the value estimations quite apparent. 

On the personality question sections, I did not think much beyond the question at head. I went through my memories of the events and tried my best to develop an accurate number of occurrences. Then I also tried to remember if there were missed opportunities for the events and then also whether they were missed due to COVID-19 avoidance.
Studying1: Whether estimation skills are a good indicator of social avoidance activities.
